         "Technique ID": "T1588",
         "Technique name": "Obtain Capabilities",
         "Quotes": "",
         "Explanation": "This rule looks for attempts to poison an SMB server by exploiting the “Responder” vulnerability (CVE-2020-14882), which could allow an attacker to execute arbitrary code on the target system."
     ],
     "sid": "50094",
     "Technique ID": "T1496",
     "Technique name": "Resource Hijacking",
     "Quotes": "",
     "Explanation": "This rule looks for attempts to poison an SMB server by exploiting the “Responder” vulnerability (CVE-2020-14882), which could allow an attacker to execute arbitrary code on the target system."
 ][
     "sid": "50094",
     "Technique ID": "T1557",
     "Technique Name": "Adversary-in-the-Middle",
     "Quotes": "Adversaries may attempt to position themselves between two or more networked devices using an adversary-in-the-middle (AiTM) technique to support follow-on behaviors such as Network Sniffing, Transmitted Data Manipulation, or replay attacks (Exploitation for Credential Access).",
     "Explanation": "This rule looks for a poisoning attack using a Responder probing for servers responding on a rogue Responder Port."
 ][
   {
     "sid": "50094",
     "Technique ID": "T1496",
     "Technique name": "Resource Hijacking",
     "Quotes": "Adversaries may leverage the resources of co-opted systems to complete resource-intensive tasks, which may impact system and/or hosted service availability",
     "Explanation": "This rule detects attempts to poison a DNS server response with a malicious image file using the Responder tool. The attacker can leverage the DNS server to redirect traffic to a malicious website or perform other malicious activities."
   },
   {
     "sid": "50094",
     "Technique ID": "T1557",
     "Technique name": "Adversary-in-the-Middle",
     "Quotes": "Adversaries may attempt to position themselves between two or more networked devices using an adversary-in-the-middle (AiTM) technique to support follow-on behaviors such as Network Sniffing, Transmitted Data Manipulation, or replay attacks (Exploitation for Credential Access)",
     "Explanation": "DNS poisoning is a type of man-in-the-middle attack where the attacker intercepts and modifies DNS responses, redirecting traffic to a malicious website. This rule detects attempts to poison a DNS server response, which can be used to perform a variety of malicious activities, including phishing, malware distribution, and data theft."
   }
 ]
